Perpetual Foreigner

The Harmful Stereotype of the Perpetual Foreigner



The Perpetual Foreigner stereotype is harmful because it assumes that individuals who are racially or ethnically different from the majority population are not truly American, regardless of how long they have lived in the United States. This stereotype erases the experiences of individuals who have grown up in the United States and view themselves as American. It also perpetuates the idea that individuals who are racially or ethnically different are not fully integrated into American society and therefore not entitled to the same rights and privileges as other Americans. This can lead to discrimination in areas such as employment, housing, and education, and can create a sense of alienation and marginalization for those wo are targeted by this stereotype.



Why it matters



This stereotype can have a particularly harmful impact on the mental health and well-being of individuals who are targeted by it. When someone is constantly reminded that they are not considered a "real" member of their society, they may begin to feel isolated, anxious, and depressed. This can lead to a variety of negative health outcomes, including stress-related illnesses, substance abuse, and suicide. The perpetual foreigner stereotype can prompt to discrimination in various facets of life. For example, individuals who are targeted by this stereotype may face discrimination in employment, housing, and education. What does it overlook



The Perpetual Foreigner stereotype overlooks the fact that individuals who are racially or ethnically different can be US citizens or legal residents. This stereotype assumes that individuals who are racially or ethnically different cannot be truly American, regardless of their citizenship status or their length of time in the United States. However, many individuals who are targeted by this stereotype are US citizens or legal residents who were born in the United States or have lived in the United States or have lived in the country for most of their lives. This assumption denies individuals the right to claim their American identity and can create a sense of alienation and marginalization. In addition, this stereotype overlooks the cultural contributions of individuals who are racially or ethnically different. For instance, Asian Americans have contributed to American cuisine, music, and fashion. The erasure of these contribution denies the richness and diversity of American culture.



What should be done



Stacey Lee in "Model Minority and the Perpetual Foreigner" points out that it is important to recognize the harmful effects of these stereotypes and to work towards creating a more inclusive and equitable society for all. Addressing the perpetual foreigner stereotype requires recognizing that individuals who are racially or ethnically different can be US citizens or legal residents, acknowledging the cultural contributions of individuals who are racially or ethnically different, and understanding the experiences of individuals who have faced discrimination and racism.
